[graphql] Define basic GraphQL query to fetch unique identities

This commit defines a basic schema and a query to retrieve
the information stored by unique identitiesn. To ask for the
list of unique identities and their related data stored by
SortingHat, a GraphQL query would be like this:

```
{
  uidentities {
    uuid
    profile {
      name
      email
      country {
         name
      }
    }
    identities {
      id
      name
      email
      username
      source
    }
    enrollments {
      organization {
        name
      }
      start
      end
    }
  }
}
```

[graphql] Define GraphQL mutation to add organizations

The mutation 'addOrganization' allows to create a new
organization in the registry. Errors are returned in
case the organization already exists or the name is
invalid.

To add an organization a mutation query like this will
work:

  mutation addOrg {
    addOrganization(name: "Example") {
      organization {
        name
      }
    }
  }

[graphql] Define GraphQL mutation to delete organizations

The mutation 'deleteOrganization' allows to remove an
organization from the registry. Errors are returned in
case the organization does not exist.

To remove an organization a mutation query like this will
work:

  mutation delOrg {
    deleteOrganization(name: "Example") {
      organization {
        name
      }
    }
  }

[graphql] Define GraphQL mutation to add domains

The mutation 'addDomain' allows to add a domain to the
registry. Errors are returned in case the organization
where this domain added does not exist, when the domain
name is empty or when it already exists in the registry.

To add a domain a mutation query like this will work:

  mutation addDom {
    addDomain(organization: "Example", domain: "example.net") {
      domain {
        domain
        isTopDomain
        organization {
          name
        }
      }
    }
  }

[graphql] Define GraphQL mutation to delete domains

The mutation 'deleteDomain' allows to remove a domain
from the registry. Errors are returned in case the domain
does not exist.

To remove a domain, a mutation query like this will work:

  mutation delDom {
    deleteDomain(domain: "example.net") {
      domain {
        domain
        isTopDomain
      }
    }
  }

[graphql] Define GraphQL mutation to delete identities

The mutation 'deleteIdentity' allows to delete existing
identities or unique identities from the registry.
By default, it removes identities but when the given
UUID belongs to a unique identity, that will be deleted.

Errors are returned either when the identity does not exist,
or when the UUID has an invalid value.

To remove an identity a mutation query like this will work:

mutation delId($uuid: String) {
  deleteIdentity(uuid: $uuid) {
    uuid
    uidentity {
      uuid
      identities {
        id
        name
        email
        username
        source
      }
    }
  }
}

[graphql] Define GraphQL mutation to update profiles

The mutation 'updateProfile' allows to update unique
identities profiles. Many attributes can be set such
as the name or email, the gender and whether the unique
identity is a bot or not.

To update the profile through a mutation, a query like
this should work:

mutation editProfile($uuid: String, $data: ProfileInputType) {
  updateProfile(uuid: $uuid, data: $data) {
    uuid
    uidentity {
      uuid
      profile {
        name
        email
        gender
        genderAcc
        isBot
        country {
          name
          code
        }
      }
    }
  }
}

[graphql] Define GraphQL mutation to enroll identities

The mutation 'enroll' allows to assign identities to
organizations for a period of time.

To enroll identities, a query like this should work:

mutation enrollId($uuid: String, $organization: String,
                  $fromDate: DateTime, $toDate: DateTime) {
  enroll(uuid: $uuid, organization: $organization
         fromDate: $fromDate, toDate: $toDate) {
    uuid
    uidentity {
      uuid
      enrollments {
        organization {
          name
        }
        start
        end
      }
    }
  }
}

[graphql] Define GraphQL mutation to withdraw identities

The mutation 'withdraw' allows to remove identities from
organizations in a period of time.

To withdraw identities, a query like this should work:

mutation enrollId($uuid: String, $organization: String,
                  $fromDate: DateTime, $toDate: DateTime) {
  withdraw(uuid: $uuid, organization: $organization
           fromDate: $fromDate, toDate: $toDate) {
    uuid
    uidentity {
      uuid
      enrollments {
        organization {
          name
        }
        start
        end
      }
    }
  }
}

[graphql] Define GraphQL mutation to move identities

The mutation 'moveIdentity' allows to move identities from
one unique identity to another.

To move identities, a query like this should work:

mutation moveId($fromID: String, $toUUID: String) {
  moveIdentity(fromId: $fromID, toUuid: $toUUID) {
    uuid
    uidentity {
      uuid
      identities {
        id
        name
        email
        username
        source
      }
    }
  }
}
